import pandas as pd

# Load your datasets
TB_data1 = pd.read_csv('tb-case-rates-in-ca.csv')
TB_data2 = pd.read_csv('tb-case-rates-by-lhj.csv')

# Merge the datasets on 'Year'
merged_df = pd.merge(TB_data1, TB_data2, how='inner', on='Year', suffixes=('_dataset1', '_dataset2'))

# Select only the columns you need and ensure there's only one instance of each
merged_df = merged_df[['Year', 'Category', 'Strata', 'Cases_dataset1', 'Population_dataset1', 
                       'Rate per 100,000 population_dataset1', 'Jurisdiction']]

# Rename columns to remove suffixes and make them consistent
merged_df.columns = ['Year', 'Category', 'Strata', 'Cases', 'Population', 
                     'Rate per 100,000 population', 'Jurisdiction']

# View the final merged dataframe
print(merged_df.head())

import numpy as np
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define your feature matrix and target vector
X = merged_df[['Cases', 'Population']]
y = merged_df['Jurisdiction']

# Step 1: Handle missing values by imputing with the mean
imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
X_imputed = imputer.fit_transform(X)  # Impute missing values in X

# Step 2: Initialize an empty list to store the Sum of Squared Errors (SSE)
SSE = []

# Step 3: Loop through different values of k (number of neighbors)
for k in range(1, 20):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_imputed, y)  # Fit the model using imputed data
    pred_i = knn.predict(X_imputed)  # Predict on the same data (for SSE calculation)
    
    # Step 4: Calculate the error (misclassification rate) and append to SSE list
    SSE.append(np.mean(pred_i != y))

# Step 5: Plot the SSE for each value of k
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
plt.plot(range(1, 20), SSE, color='b', linestyle='dashed', marker='o',
         markerfacecolor='r', markersize=10)
plt.xlabel('Number of Neighbors (k)')
plt.ylabel('Error Rate')
plt.title('Error Rate vs. K Value')
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Drop rows with missing values in 'Cases' and 'Population'
merged_df.dropna(subset=['Cases', 'Population'], inplace=True)

# Select features and target
X = merged_df[['Cases', 'Population']].values
y = merged_df['Jurisdiction']

# Encode the target variable (if it's categorical)
le = LabelEncoder()
y = le.fit_transform(y)

# Split data into train and test sets (optional)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Define KNN model
n_neighbors = 6
h = 100  # Increased step size to reduce memory usage
clf = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n_neighbors, weights='distance')
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Define the min and max of the grid for plotting, limit the range to avoid memory overload
x_min, x_max = np.percentile(X[:, 0], [2, 98])  # Clip extreme values at 2nd and 98th percentile
y_min, y_max = np.percentile(X[:, 1], [2, 98])

# Create a mesh grid with reduced resolution
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h), np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))

# Predict for each point in the grid
Z = clf.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)

# Create color maps
cmap_light = ListedColormap(['#FFAAAA', '#AAFFAA', '#AAAAFF'])
cmap_bold = ListedColormap(['#FF0000', '#00FF00', '#0000FF'])

# Plot the decision boundary
plt.figure()
plt.pcolormesh(xx, yy, Z, cmap=cmap_light)

# Plot the training points
plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, cmap=cmap_bold, edgecolor='k', s=20)
plt.xlim(xx.min(), xx.max())
plt.ylim(yy.min(), yy.max())
plt.title(f"Classification using KNN (k = {n_neighbors})")

plt.show()

In[14]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# Sample data creation for demonstration purposes
np.random.seed(0)
data = {
    'Cases': np.random.randint(1, 1000, 1000),
    'Population': np.random.randint(1, 10000, 1000),
    'Jurisdiction': np.random.choice(['A', 'B', 'C'], 1000)  # Example categories}
merged_df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Drop rows with missing values in 'Cases' and 'Population'
merged_df.dropna(subset=['Cases', 'Population'], inplace=True)

# Select features and target
X = merged_df[['Cases', 'Population']].values
y = merged_df['Jurisdiction']

# Encode the target variable
le = LabelEncoder()
y = le.fit_transform(y)

# Split data into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# --- KNN Classification ---
# Define KNN model
n_neighbors = 6
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n_neighbors)
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict on the test set
y_pred_knn = knn.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy for KNN
accuracy_knn = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_knn)

# Create a mesh grid for KNN decision boundary
x_min, x_max = np.percentile(X[:, 0], [2, 98])
y_min, y_max = np.percentile(X[:, 1], [2, 98])
h = 100  # Step size for meshgrid
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h), np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))

# Predict for each point in the grid for KNN
Z_knn = knn.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
Z_knn = Z_knn.reshape(xx.shape)

# Create color maps for KNN
cmap_light = ListedColormap(['#FFAAAA', '#AAFFAA', '#AAAAFF'])
cmap_bold = ListedColormap(['#FF0000', '#00FF00', '#0000FF'])

# Plot KNN decision boundary
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.pcolormesh(xx, yy, Z_knn, cmap=cmap_light, alpha=0.5)
plt.scatter(X_test[:, 0], X_test[:, 1], c=y_pred_knn, cmap='summer', edgecolor='k', s=20)
plt.title(f"KNN Classification (k = {n_neighbors}, Accuracy: {accuracy_knn:.2f})")
plt.xlabel('Cases')
plt.ylabel('Population')
plt.colorbar(label='Predicted Class')
plt.show()

# --- Nave Bayes Classification ---
# Define Nave Bayes model
nb = GaussianNB()
nb.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict on the test set
y_pred_nb = nb.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy for Nave Bayes
accuracy_nb = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_nb)

# Create a mesh grid for Nave Bayes decision boundary
Z_nb = nb.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
Z_nb = Z_nb.reshape(xx.shape)

# Plot Nave Bayes decision boundary
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.pcolormesh(xx, yy, Z_nb, cmap=cmap_light, alpha=0.5)
plt.scatter(X_test[:, 0], X_test[:, 1], c=y_pred_nb, cmap='summer', edgecolor='k', s=20)
plt.title(f"Nave Bayes Classification (Accuracy: {accuracy_nb:.2f})")
plt.xlabel('Cases')
plt.ylabel('Population')
plt.colorbar(label='Predicted Class')
plt.show()

# Report accuracies
print(f"KNN Accuracy: {accuracy_knn:.2f}")
print(f"Nave Bayes Accuracy: {accuracy_nb:.2f}")

# Determine which model works better
if accuracy_knn > accuracy_nb:
    print("KNN works better for this data.")
else:
    print("Nave Bayes works better for this data.")

KNN Accuracy: 0.35
Nave Bayes Accuracy: 0.33
KNN works better for this data.

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Select features and target
X = merged_df[['Cases', 'Population']].values
y = merged_df['Jurisdiction']

# Encode the target variable
le = LabelEncoder()
y = le.fit_transform(y)

# Scale the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Split data into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# --- KNN Classification ---
n_neighbors = 6
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n_neighbors, weights='distance')
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_knn = knn.predict(X_test)
accuracy_knn = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_knn)

# Print detailed KNN metrics
print("KNN Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_knn))

# Create visualization grid
x_min, x_max = X_scaled[:, 0].min() - 1, X_scaled[:, 0].max() + 1
y_min, y_max = X_scaled[:, 1].min() - 1, X_scaled[:, 1].max() + 1
h = 0.02  # Step size for visualization
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h), np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))

# KNN Decision boundary
Z_knn = knn.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
Z_knn = Z_knn.reshape(xx.shape)

# Create color maps
cmap_light = ListedColormap(['#FFAAAA', '#AAFFAA', '#AAAAFF'])
cmap_bold = ListedColormap(['#FF0000', '#00FF00', '#0000FF'])

# Plot KNN
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.pcolormesh(xx, yy, Z_knn, cmap=cmap_light, alpha=0.5)
plt.scatter(X_test[:, 0], X_test[:, 1], c=y_test, cmap=cmap_bold, edgecolor='k', s=20)
plt.title(f"KNN Classification (k={n_neighbors}, Accuracy: {accuracy_knn:.2f})")
plt.xlabel('Cases (scaled)')
plt.ylabel('Population (scaled)')
plt.colorbar(label='Predicted Class')
plt.show()

# --- Nave Bayes Classification ---
nb = GaussianNB()
nb.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_nb = nb.predict(X_test)
accuracy_nb = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_nb)

# Print detailed Naive Bayes metrics
print("\nNaive Bayes Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_nb))

# Nave Bayes Decision boundary
Z_nb = nb.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
Z_nb = Z_nb.reshape(xx.shape)

# Plot Nave Bayes
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.pcolormesh(xx, yy, Z_nb, cmap=cmap_light, alpha=0.5)
plt.scatter(X_test[:, 0], X_test[:, 1], c=y_test, cmap=cmap_bold, edgecolor='k', s=20)
plt.title(f"Nave Bayes Classification (Accuracy: {accuracy_nb:.2f})")
plt.xlabel('Cases (scaled)')
plt.ylabel('Population (scaled)')
plt.colorbar(label='Predicted Class')
plt.show()

# Report final results
print("\nFinal Results:")
print(f"KNN Accuracy: {accuracy_knn:.2f}")
print(f"Nave Bayes Accuracy: {accuracy_nb:.2f}")
print(f"{'KNN' if accuracy_knn > accuracy_nb else 'Nave Bayes'} works better for this data.")
